Yes, you will go through
a transition period,

55:32.496 --> 55:34.530
but once your taste buds,
and your body's chemistry

55:34.532 --> 55:37.099
begins to change, you
will start to crave

55:37.101 --> 55:38.901
and really enjoy these foods.

55:40.003 --> 55:42.504
It is important to
find food you like,

55:42.506 --> 55:44.406
and once you realize
that almost every dish

55:44.408 --> 55:46.475
can be made plant-based,
you will see that

55:46.477 --> 55:48.544
it is not that hard at all.

55:50.613 --> 55:52.881
- There's such a stigma
with the word vegan,

55:52.883 --> 55:54.883
I guess that people
just get automatically

55:54.885 --> 55:56.719
turned off and just assume
that it's going to suck.

55:56.721 --> 55:57.986
But it's like it doesn't.

55:57.988 --> 55:59.388
If anything, to me, and
i mean, that was another

55:59.390 --> 56:01.557
big thing, why I do it,
because it's better.

56:01.559 --> 56:03.592
To me, I think food's
just way better this way.

56:03.594 --> 56:05.461
I would say just try it.

56:05.463 --> 56:07.396
You know, you'll
surprise yourself.

56:07.398 --> 56:09.531
- When you're
becoming vegetarian,

56:09.533 --> 56:11.367
and you've given up
the meat and the dairy

56:11.369 --> 56:13.435
and the eggs, the only
thing you know for food,

56:13.437 --> 56:14.937
you think you're going
to starve to death.

56:15.872 --> 56:17.773
You have to understand that

56:17.775 --> 56:19.742
marinara sauce, and
pasta, and lasagna,

56:19.744 --> 56:24.079
and bean burritos, and oatmeal,
and hash-brown potatoes,

56:24.081 --> 56:26.949
and so on, things you
love, that's where you get

56:26.951 --> 56:29.084
your calories and your
protein and your vitamins

56:29.086 --> 56:30.886
and your minerals.

56:30.888 --> 56:32.755
- There are so many
beautiful, wonderful

56:32.757 --> 56:36.392
amazing, delicious
plant-based foods out there.

56:36.394 --> 56:38.894
In fact, when I started
to do this a whole world

56:38.896 --> 56:41.530
opened up to me, and
when you begin to eat

56:41.532 --> 56:44.466
these nutrient dense
foods that are actually

56:44.468 --> 56:47.870
fuelling you, that are
actually nourishing you,

56:47.872 --> 56:49.905
with all of these
amazing vital nutrients

56:49.907 --> 56:52.708
and micronutrients,
you start to feel good,

56:52.710 --> 56:55.778
your cravings change, and
your taste buds change.

56:55.780 --> 56:57.913
You know, that cheeseburger,
that you couldn't

56:57.915 --> 56:59.948
get out of your mind, suddenly,

56:59.950 --> 57:01.750
you're not thinking
about that anymore,

57:01.752 --> 57:04.586
and you're actually
craving that Kale smoothie.

57:04.588 --> 57:06.054
And that's something
that happened to me

57:06.056 --> 57:08.023
that I would have never
thought would have happened.

57:08.025 --> 57:10.125
- People think that vegan
food just tastes like crap.

57:10.127 --> 57:11.727
And that's not true.

57:11.729 --> 57:13.128
I think that people
think that being vegan

57:13.130 --> 57:14.930
might potentially be strange,

57:14.932 --> 57:17.666
that people are weird, that
you have to be a hippie,

57:17.668 --> 57:19.768
or you have to embrace
wearing hemp clothes,

57:19.770 --> 57:21.203
or something.

57:21.205 --> 57:22.571
- You want to have a burger,
you can have a burger.

57:22.573 --> 57:23.872
You want to have
spaghetti and meatballs,

57:23.874 --> 57:25.841
you can have spaghetti
and wheatballs.

57:25.843 --> 57:27.209
You want to have fries,
you want to have chocolate

57:27.211 --> 57:30.479
mousse, you want to
have pumpkin pie,

57:30.481 --> 57:32.581
you want to have stuffing,
you want to have,

57:32.583 --> 57:35.484
you know, even hotdogs.

57:35.486 --> 57:37.653
- And so when you're looking at

57:37.655 --> 57:40.155
the idea of taking the leap,

57:40.157 --> 57:42.691
into this way of
eating and living,

57:42.693 --> 57:44.560
don't look at what
you're going to be

57:44.562 --> 57:47.963
not eating, embrace
and be excited

57:47.965 --> 57:50.766
about the adventure
of all these new foods

57:50.768 --> 57:52.634
you're going to be
bringing into your life.

57:53.870 --> 57:55.204
- Eating
healthy will not do you

57:55.206 --> 57:57.673
much good if you
can't afford it.

57:57.675 --> 58:00.008
Or if it leaves a big
hole in your pocket.

58:00.010 --> 58:02.478
So my next question
was is it possible

58:02.480 --> 58:04.746
to eat healthy on
a tight budget?

58:06.783 --> 58:09.718
- A common misconception
is that a whole

58:09.720 --> 58:12.754
foods plant-based diet
is very expensive.

58:12.756 --> 58:17.726
I routinely post pictures
of my grocery receipt,

58:17.728 --> 58:19.495
and I take my whole
bounty that I bought

58:19.497 --> 58:22.030
at the produce market, and
put it out on the table

58:22.032 --> 58:25.667
so people can see, how
much I end up with,

58:25.669 --> 58:26.969
and they're shocked.

58:26.971 --> 58:29.671
Whole grains that
we buy in bulk,

58:29.673 --> 58:31.673
are very inexpensive.

58:31.675 --> 58:34.176
You're going to cut your
grocery bills in half,

58:34.178 --> 58:36.278
from a typical
standard American diet,

58:36.280 --> 58:38.747
in the beginning, it might
seem like a lot of effort,

58:38.749 --> 58:40.649
but in the long run, you're
saving all this money

58:40.651 --> 58:42.851
for all the new clothes
you're going to have to buy

58:42.853 --> 58:45.721
for the new slim
you that is produced

58:45.723 --> 58:48.690
from eating this whole
foods plant-based diet.

58:48.692 --> 58:50.659
- It's easy to go into
those markets and say,

58:50.661 --> 58:52.261
"there's no way
that I can do this."

58:52.263 --> 58:53.795
But the truth of
the matter is that

58:53.797 --> 58:56.164
it doesn't have to be expensive,

58:56.166 --> 58:57.766
it doesn't have to
be inconvenient,

58:57.768 --> 58:59.268
it doesn't have to be
difficult, it doesn't have

58:59.270 --> 59:01.036
to be time consuming.

59:01.038 --> 59:03.171
And my experience is
that it has actually

59:03.173 --> 59:05.707
simplified my life,
and it's been cheaper

59:05.709 --> 59:07.776
than eating the
other way around.

59:09.546 --> 59:10.913
- At this
point of my journey,

59:10.915 --> 59:12.681
I already had seen
enough evidence

59:12.683 --> 59:15.884
about the benefits and
safety of a plant based diet

59:15.886 --> 59:19.154
for adults, but was this
lifestyle also ideal

59:19.156 --> 59:21.089
and safe for children?

59:22.926 --> 59:25.727
- Not only can
children grow healthy

59:25.729 --> 59:27.563
on a plant-based
diet, they'll grow

59:27.565 --> 59:29.765
healthiest on a
plant-based diet.

59:29.767 --> 59:31.266
I mean, we have an
epidemic of childhood

59:31.268 --> 59:36.004
obesity, and children
raised plant-based,

59:36.006 --> 59:37.739
actually grow taller
by about an inch,

59:37.741 --> 59:39.775
they grow about an inch
taller than meat eating

59:39.777 --> 59:41.677
incumbents, and
most importantly,

59:41.679 --> 59:45.147
they grow less in a
horizontal direction, right?

59:45.149 --> 59:46.982
They don't have
the same problems

59:46.984 --> 59:50.586
with childhood obesity,
so Dr. Benjamin Spock,

59:50.588 --> 59:53.355
the most esteemed
pediatrician of all time,

59:53.357 --> 59:54.823
wrote one of the
bestselling books

59:54.825 --> 59:57.059
in human history,
recommended in his final

59:57.061 --> 01:00:00.195
edition, the 7th edition
of his book before he died

01:00:00.197 --> 01:00:02.998
in his 90's, that all
children should be raised

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:06.068
with zero exposure
to meat and dairy.

01:00:06.070 --> 01:00:07.302
And he did this
because he saw what

01:00:07.304 --> 01:00:09.338
you know, the older
generations were dying

01:00:09.340 --> 01:00:12.674
from, and wanted to get
them off on a good start.

01:00:12.676 --> 01:00:16.812
I mean the leading
killers of our children

01:00:17.614 --> 01:00:20.315
will eventually be, same thing.

01:00:20.317 --> 01:00:22.117
Heart disease,
cancer, strokes, copd,

01:00:22.119 --> 01:00:24.620
diabetes, hypertension.

01:00:24.622 --> 01:00:26.021
These are diseases
that can be prevented

01:00:26.023 --> 01:00:28.824
in many cases arrested,
or even reversed

01:00:28.826 --> 01:00:30.859
with a healthy enough
plant-based diet.

01:00:32.261 --> 01:00:33.895
- As a new
father, I wondered,

01:00:33.897 --> 01:00:36.231
how could I get my
daughter to eat healthy?

01:00:36.233 --> 01:00:37.833
Since getting her to
eat anything at all

01:00:37.835 --> 01:00:40.202
can sometimes be a problem.

01:00:40.204 --> 01:00:41.803
There's so much
junk being marketed

01:00:41.805 --> 01:00:44.339
to kids out there, and
it is often difficult

01:00:44.341 --> 01:00:46.842
for parents to
transition their children

01:00:46.844 --> 01:00:48.744
to healthier food options.

01:00:50.346 --> 01:00:52.381
- I would not be
surprised at all

01:00:52.383 --> 01:00:56.284
that if in 15,
20, 25 years time,

01:00:57.654 --> 01:01:01.957
people will look back at
the last 10 to 20 years,

01:01:01.959 --> 01:01:06.862
and they'll say, "how did
those people give that food

01:01:06.864 --> 01:01:08.063
"to their children?"

01:01:12.268 --> 01:01:13.969
- A big question that
we get all the time

01:01:13.971 --> 01:01:16.772
is, "how can I get my
kids to eat better?"

01:01:16.774 --> 01:01:19.341
I think every parent
wants their kids to eat

01:01:19.343 --> 01:01:24.079
healthy, and it's
difficult, especially when

01:01:24.081 --> 01:01:25.881
everywhere you look, there's
a fast food restaurant,

01:01:25.883 --> 01:01:28.450
or a processed food snack
that is being marketed

01:01:28.452 --> 01:01:30.085
towards children.

01:01:30.087 --> 01:01:31.420
And the first thing
that I always say is,

01:01:31.422 --> 01:01:33.889
"you have to lead by example."

01:01:33.891 --> 01:01:36.324
As a parent, you can't
be eating lousy foods,

01:01:36.326 --> 01:01:38.927
and expect your
children to eat healthy,

01:01:38.929 --> 01:01:40.295
because you tell them to.

01:01:40.297 --> 01:01:43.398
So you have to walk your
walk, that's number one.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:45.867
The second thing is, i
encourage all parents

01:01:47.270 --> 01:01:51.073
to make the preparation
of meals and the shopping

01:01:51.075 --> 01:01:53.842
of food inclusive
with their children.

01:01:53.844 --> 01:01:57.245
The more you can bring
your kids into the fold,

01:01:57.247 --> 01:02:00.415
the more they're going
to develop an emotional

01:02:00.417 --> 01:02:03.719
attachment to where
their food comes from,

01:02:03.721 --> 01:02:05.053
how it's prepared,
and the impact that

01:02:05.055 --> 01:02:06.888
it's having on their health.

01:02:06.890 --> 01:02:08.423
- Really get inside their heads,

01:02:08.425 --> 01:02:10.826
and sort of think
how they would think.

01:02:10.828 --> 01:02:14.162
Keep telling them what
is good, what is bad,

01:02:14.164 --> 01:02:17.966
won't probably work, you
have to interact with them,

01:02:17.968 --> 01:02:20.302
you have to show
them what's possible.

01:02:20.304 --> 01:02:23.205
Get your hands dirty,
get the kids to help you,

01:02:23.207 --> 01:02:25.107
and let them own
what they're doing.

01:02:26.909 --> 01:02:29.211
If you always put
something in front of them

01:02:29.213 --> 01:02:31.813
in a silver platter,
and let them consume

01:02:31.815 --> 01:02:33.815
that information,
you know, it'll only

01:02:33.817 --> 01:02:33.815
work for so long.

01:02:33.817 --> 01:02:33.815
What you've got to do,
you've got to get them

01:02:33.817 --> 01:02:39.988
involved, let them have
the responsibility.

01:02:39.990 --> 01:02:42.290
The way I approach it
is that I try to make it

01:02:42.292 --> 01:02:45.427
as fun as possible, use
colors, use flavors,

01:02:46.963 --> 01:02:48.997
teach a little thing that
they never knew about,

01:02:48.999 --> 01:02:53.335
use gadgets that,
normal people won't see,

01:02:53.337 --> 01:02:55.837
but I want them to go
away with a feeling

01:02:55.839 --> 01:02:58.073
of accomplishment,
and something that

01:02:58.075 --> 01:03:00.909
they're eager to share
to their friends.

01:03:01.844 --> 01:03:03.211
Hopefully their parents.

01:03:03.213 --> 01:03:04.846
I think that's the best part.

01:03:04.848 --> 01:03:06.114
It's like holding a bird.

01:03:06.116 --> 01:03:07.949
You don't want to
hold it too tight,

01:03:07.951 --> 01:03:07.949
you're going to hurt the bird.

01:03:07.951 --> 01:03:10.318
You don't want to
hold it too loosely,

01:03:10.320 --> 01:03:11.920
or it's going to fly away.

01:03:11.922 --> 01:03:13.555
That's something that
each individual parent

01:03:13.557 --> 01:03:16.992
has a specific
knowledge of their kid.

01:03:16.994 --> 01:03:18.860
- I get the questions
all the time.

01:03:18.862 --> 01:03:20.896
"What do I do, how do I start,

01:03:20.898 --> 01:03:22.798
"how do I tell my kids,
oh, they're going to be

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:22.798
"so disappointed that
they're not having

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:27.202
"meat on their plates, that
they're not having dairy."

01:03:27.204 --> 01:03:30.272
Try a vegan burger, it's
basically the same thing,

01:03:30.274 --> 01:03:31.940
you just leave the meat out.

01:03:31.942 --> 01:03:31.940
That's great for
kids, because why?

01:03:31.942 --> 01:03:34.876
You're going to put
that burger on that bun,

01:03:34.878 --> 01:03:36.845
you're going to put all
the fixings on that,

01:03:36.847 --> 01:03:39.214
whatever your kids like, you
make it exactly the same,

01:03:39.216 --> 01:03:41.583
that's a great way
to get started.

01:03:41.585 --> 01:03:43.084
- When I think with
the younger generation,

01:03:43.086 --> 01:03:45.287
what's so exciting is,
is that they get to start

01:03:45.289 --> 01:03:49.958
young, I mean, I'm not
going to have any regrets,

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:51.226
but it sort of bums me
out a little bit that I'm

01:03:51.228 --> 01:03:53.595
just now discovering
this in my 30's because

01:03:53.597 --> 01:03:55.997
I wish I would have done
this when I was younger,

01:03:55.999 --> 01:03:58.500
because just the thoughts
of like the energy,

01:03:58.502 --> 01:04:00.969
that I would've had in college.

01:04:00.971 --> 01:04:03.338
- I think the other
thing is to not have

01:04:03.340 --> 01:04:06.274
hard and fast rules,
with your children,

01:04:06.276 --> 01:04:09.845
you can't eat that, and you
know, you have to eat this.

01:04:09.847 --> 01:04:14.249
And instead, respect them as
independent sentient beings,

01:04:14.251 --> 01:04:16.551
who have you know,
the wherewithal

01:04:16.553 --> 01:04:19.521
to make conscious
decisions for themselves.

01:04:19.523 --> 01:04:23.058
So, at our home, we
serve plant based foods,

01:04:23.060 --> 01:04:24.993
all the time, we don't
have any animal products

01:04:24.995 --> 01:04:27.896
here, but when my 10
year old daughter goes

01:04:27.898 --> 01:04:31.166
to a birthday party, she's
surrounded by you know,

01:04:31.168 --> 01:04:34.269
chicken McNuggets, and
birthday cake and all of that,

01:04:34.271 --> 01:04:38.106
and we don't say to her,
"you can't eat those foods."

01:04:38.108 --> 01:04:41.243
We say, "have a great time
at the birthday party,

01:04:41.245 --> 01:04:44.045
"and make the right
choice for you."

01:04:44.047 --> 01:04:45.447
And that doesn't mean
that she always makes

01:04:45.449 --> 01:04:49.618
the right choice, that
way you are empowering

01:04:49.620 --> 01:04:51.953
them, this is a lifetime
we're talking about.

01:04:51.955 --> 01:04:54.389
This is a long road ahead,
so it's about getting

01:04:54.391 --> 01:04:56.958
your children to think
consciously about their

01:04:56.960 --> 01:04:59.261
own choices, so that
when they reach the age

01:04:59.263 --> 01:05:02.163
of maturity, they are
informed and educated

01:05:02.165 --> 01:05:06.902
and prepared to be responsible
stewards of the planet,

01:05:06.904 --> 01:05:09.170
and responsible stewards
of their own bodies.

01:05:10.306 --> 01:05:12.207
- I could not
make a film about food choices

01:05:12.209 --> 01:05:15.043
and not explore the
topic of organic,

01:05:15.045 --> 01:05:16.945
versus non-organic.

01:05:16.947 --> 01:05:18.280
It seems that
everybody's obssessed

01:05:18.282 --> 01:05:20.682
with those words, and
it's becoming increasingly

01:05:20.684 --> 01:05:24.986
adverse to foods that don't
carry an organic label.

01:05:24.988 --> 01:05:27.222
Others fear that consuming
more plant based food

01:05:27.224 --> 01:05:29.157
might be damaging
to their health,

01:05:29.159 --> 01:05:32.627
due to the increase of
pesticides in those foods.

01:05:32.629 --> 01:05:35.196
But should this really
be our biggest concern?

01:05:36.933 --> 01:05:39.567
- Fear of pesticides
should never keep anyone

01:05:39.569 --> 01:05:42.437
from maximizing their
fruit and vegetable intake.

01:05:42.439 --> 01:05:46.141
There, you know, so there's
been like chemic computer

01:05:46.143 --> 01:05:49.177
modeling studies that
suggest that, so for example,

01:05:49.179 --> 01:05:51.179
if half of Americans ate
a single more serving

01:05:51.181 --> 01:05:53.148
of fruits and vegetables
a day, we'd prevent

01:05:53.150 --> 01:05:56.451
20,000 cancer deaths every year.

01:05:56.453 --> 01:05:58.520
If just half the people,
just one more serving,

01:05:58.522 --> 01:06:02.357
20,000 people would not
have died from cancer,

01:06:02.359 --> 01:06:04.559
would normally have died
if they hadn't done that.

01:06:04.561 --> 01:06:06.728
So that's how powerful
fruits and vegetables are.

01:06:06.730 --> 01:06:10.365
But, because these
were conventional,

01:06:10.367 --> 01:06:12.567
pesticide laden
fruits and vegetables,

01:06:12.569 --> 01:06:15.470
they estimated that it
would, that the extra

01:06:15.472 --> 01:06:17.238
pesticide burden from
all those extra fruits

01:06:17.240 --> 01:06:20.175
and vegetables would cause 10

01:06:20.177 --> 01:06:21.609
extra cancer deaths.

01:06:21.611 --> 01:06:26.147
So in all it would only
prevent 19, 990 cancer deaths.

01:06:26.149 --> 01:06:27.983
But that's what we're
looking at a year,

01:06:27.985 --> 01:06:29.684
this tremendous benefit.

01:06:29.686 --> 01:06:31.252
Then a tiny bump in risk.

01:06:31.254 --> 01:06:33.688
So, okay, great, choose
organic whenever you can,

01:06:33.690 --> 01:06:36.291
why accept any risk,
why not get all benefit?

01:06:36.293 --> 01:06:39.227
Sure, but we should never
let concern about pesticides

01:06:39.229 --> 01:06:42.230
in any way dissuade us
from stuffing our face

01:06:42.232 --> 01:06:45.400
with as many healthy fruits
and vegetables as possible.

01:06:45.402 --> 01:06:47.769
- If you're eating meat,
and you're eating commercial

01:06:47.771 --> 01:06:50.138
meat, and you're worried
about switching to plant-based

01:06:50.140 --> 01:06:53.274
diet, and worried about the
pesticides in the produce,

01:06:53.276 --> 01:06:54.743
you're being ridiculous,
because you're getting

01:06:54.745 --> 01:06:57.746
a fraction of the pesticides
by eating the vegetable,

01:06:58.681 --> 01:07:00.248
that you can mostly wash it off.

01:07:00.250 --> 01:07:01.750
Remember, you can
wash, you can soak your

01:07:01.752 --> 01:07:04.219
vegetables and use a
wash to get pesticide

01:07:04.221 --> 01:07:04.219
residue off.

01:07:04.221 --> 01:07:08.123
You cannot wash the pesticide
off of the hamburger

01:07:08.125 --> 01:07:09.657
meat you're about to prepare.

01:07:09.659 --> 01:07:12.060
- I encourage people
just to go ahead and buy

01:07:12.062 --> 01:07:14.229
whatever produce
they can afford,

01:07:14.231 --> 01:07:16.097
whatever produce
looks the freshest

01:07:16.099 --> 01:07:18.099
that week in the grocery store,

01:07:18.101 --> 01:07:19.701
and whatever's on sale,

01:07:19.703 --> 01:07:21.436
so that's where they're
going to save money,

01:07:21.438 --> 01:07:24.039
is not worrying about,

01:07:24.041 --> 01:07:25.707
"i have to buy
organic bell peppers,

01:07:25.709 --> 01:07:28.143
"and they cost me
four dollars each."

01:07:28.145 --> 01:07:31.613
That's not a
sustainable lifestyle.

01:07:42.291 --> 01:07:43.758
- Besides
the health aspect related

01:07:43.760 --> 01:07:46.828
to our food choices, I also
realized during the production

01:07:46.830 --> 01:07:49.697
of this film, that there
was another very important

01:07:49.699 --> 01:07:52.734
factor, that is
often overlooked,

01:07:52.736 --> 01:07:54.602
ignored, or misunderstood.

01:07:55.604 --> 01:07:57.672
The connection
between food choices,

01:07:57.674 --> 01:07:57.672
and the environment.

01:07:57.674 --> 01:08:01.309
I was really shocked after
reading the united nations

01:08:01.311 --> 01:08:03.344
report on global warming.

01:08:03.346 --> 01:08:06.081
After all, it is hard
to grasp the idea

01:08:06.083 --> 01:08:08.116
that the burger, or
steak on our plates

01:08:08.118 --> 01:08:10.251
might be contributing
to things such as

01:08:10.253 --> 01:08:12.854
global warming, water scarcity,

01:08:12.856 --> 01:08:17.158
species extinction,
the destruction of
the Amazon forest,

01:08:17.160 --> 01:08:21.162
the depletion of our oceans,
and even world hunger.

01:08:21.163 --> 01:08:23.631
I had a hard time
understanding it at first,

01:08:23.633 --> 01:08:26.234
but once I began
digging a little deeper,

01:08:26.236 --> 01:08:28.269
the connection became clear.

01:08:30.805 --> 01:08:32.474
- Now, it's seven
billion people,

01:08:32.475 --> 01:08:34.876
what we eat, determines
how the whole planet

01:08:34.877 --> 01:08:37.779
is used, and what's
happening now

01:08:37.781 --> 01:08:40.180
is that, as we run out of land,

01:08:40.183 --> 01:08:41.549
to grow these
animals and the food

01:08:41.551 --> 01:08:44.486
for the animals, we
burn down rain forests,

01:08:44.488 --> 01:08:46.621
to aquire more land.

01:08:46.622 --> 01:08:48.122
And the number one
cause of all of that

01:08:48.125 --> 01:08:49.390
is our food choices.

01:08:57.533 --> 01:09:00.201
- It's expected to have a
40% shortage in fresh water

01:09:00.203 --> 01:09:02.804
supplies by the year 2030.

01:09:02.805 --> 01:09:06.908
We have again, irreversible
loss of biodiversity,

01:09:06.910 --> 01:09:09.544
ecosystems, and extinction
of species faster than

01:09:09.546 --> 01:09:13.281
we've ever seen before, for
the past 65 million years.

01:09:13.283 --> 01:09:15.483
We have a world hunger
issue with a little less

01:09:15.484 --> 01:09:18.219
that a billion people on
earth suffering from hunger,

01:09:18.220 --> 01:09:22.290
with about 350 children
dying from hunger each hour.

01:09:24.727 --> 01:09:26.528
- You might
be asking yourself,

01:09:26.529 --> 01:09:28.563
how is all that possible?

01:09:28.564 --> 01:09:30.430
And I had the same questions,

01:09:30.433 --> 01:09:33.234
because in fact,
many of these issues

01:09:33.236 --> 01:09:36.237
are not only related
to our food choices.

01:09:36.238 --> 01:09:38.238
Many are very complex problems,

01:09:38.241 --> 01:09:41.276
with several social,
political, economic,

01:09:41.278 --> 01:09:43.444
and cultural variables.

01:09:43.446 --> 01:09:45.913
But here are some
intriguing facts.

01:09:45.916 --> 01:09:49.716
70% of our arable land
is used to grow crops

01:09:49.719 --> 01:09:52.420
for animals and not humans.

01:09:53.322 --> 01:09:56.891
It takes on average
2400 gallons of water

01:09:56.893 --> 01:10:00.228
and 12 pounds of grain to
make one pound of beef.

01:10:01.463 --> 01:10:04.432
Five million acres of
rainforest are destroyed

01:10:04.434 --> 01:10:07.936
every year, so companies
can graze animals

01:10:07.938 --> 01:10:09.737
and grow food for these animals.

01:10:10.873 --> 01:10:13.741
The excrements of 80
billion land animals

01:10:13.743 --> 01:10:17.579
killed every year for
food are not treated.

01:10:17.581 --> 01:10:19.781
And go back into
our water basins,

01:10:19.783 --> 01:10:23.384
and our oceans, creating
a lot of pollution.

01:10:23.386 --> 01:10:24.953
And these are just
a few examples.

01:10:25.955 --> 01:10:27.555
So when you consider
these facts,

01:10:28.524 --> 01:10:30.458
it all begins to
fall into place.

01:10:32.661 --> 01:10:34.295
- We need to focus
more, and understand

01:10:34.297 --> 01:10:36.431
more what the footprint
is, the complete

01:10:36.433 --> 01:10:40.301
life cycle analysis, ecological
environmental depleting

01:10:40.303 --> 01:10:44.339
footprint is of that
item is versus just how

01:10:44.341 --> 01:10:45.573
close it is to you.

01:10:45.575 --> 01:10:47.242
Or whether it's
even organic or not.

01:10:47.244 --> 01:10:49.377
It's much less of a
footprint to eat something

01:10:49.379 --> 01:10:52.347
that was grown 1500 miles away,

01:10:52.349 --> 01:10:54.949
if it was plant-based,
than it is to eat

01:10:54.951 --> 01:10:57.418
a food item that
was slaughtered,

01:10:57.420 --> 01:10:58.386
that was an animal product,

01:10:58.388 --> 01:10:59.454
by your next door neighbor.

01:10:59.456 --> 01:11:00.755
And our largest footprint is,

01:11:00.757 --> 01:11:03.358
you know, across all sectors,

01:11:03.360 --> 01:11:04.892
our food choice
specifically as it relates

01:11:04.894 --> 01:11:04.892
to eating animals.

01:11:07.563 --> 01:11:09.764
- No matter
how green, or eco-friendly

01:11:09.766 --> 01:11:12.867
we try to be, the truth
is that by nature,

01:11:12.869 --> 01:11:15.837
we are a very
destructive species.

01:11:15.839 --> 01:11:17.805
Almost everything
we do has a negative

01:11:17.807 --> 01:11:19.540
impact on the environment.

01:11:20.709 --> 01:11:23.478
So many people often try to
minimize their footprint,

01:11:23.480 --> 01:11:25.713
by doing things like
switching to more effective

01:11:25.715 --> 01:11:29.017
light bulbs, taking
short showers,

01:11:29.019 --> 01:11:32.353
bicycling to work,
using solar energy,

01:11:32.355 --> 01:11:34.756
or even buying an electric car.

01:11:34.758 --> 01:11:37.058
And those are all great things.

01:11:37.060 --> 01:11:38.626
But the question is,

01:11:38.628 --> 01:11:40.795
are these actions
in fact the easiest

01:11:40.797 --> 01:11:43.665
and most effective when
it comes to helping

01:11:43.667 --> 01:11:46.434
protect our planet
and its' resources?

01:11:47.736 --> 01:11:49.704
- You look at the
four major problems.

01:11:49.706 --> 01:11:51.706
We've got overpopulation,

01:11:51.708 --> 01:11:53.408
and we're adding about
a million people every

01:11:53.410 --> 01:11:54.809
four days, net.

01:11:54.811 --> 01:11:56.511
Then you get to the way we live,

01:11:56.513 --> 01:11:58.446
and the way we consume stuff,

01:11:58.448 --> 01:12:01.649
all that stuff is coming
from finite resources

01:12:01.651 --> 01:12:04.352
which we are steadily depleting.

01:12:04.354 --> 01:12:06.454
So those first two factors
the overpopulation,

01:12:06.456 --> 01:12:09.657
and the way we live, are
driving the third one,

01:12:09.659 --> 01:12:12.493
which is our dependence
on fossil fuels.

01:12:12.495 --> 01:12:13.828
Look at the numbers.

01:12:13.830 --> 01:12:16.898
Since 1950, the
line for consumption

01:12:16.900 --> 01:12:19.967
of fossil fuels have
gone steadily up,

01:12:19.969 --> 01:12:22.970
every year, and there's
no end in sight.

01:12:22.972 --> 01:12:25.606
The fourth big driver,
of all of these

01:12:25.608 --> 01:12:29.110
environmental issues,
particularly global warming,

01:12:29.112 --> 01:12:31.446
is the way we eat,
is our consumption

01:12:31.448 --> 01:12:32.814
of the meat, dairy,
eggs and fish,

01:12:32.816 --> 01:12:34.415
and that keeps going up.

01:12:34.417 --> 01:12:38.019
It requires, per calorie,
over 10 times as much

01:12:38.021 --> 01:12:40.688
land, 10 times as much water,

01:12:40.690 --> 01:12:42.657
and 10 times as much energy.

01:12:42.659 --> 01:12:43.891
And it ranges.

01:12:43.893 --> 01:12:45.560
But the average is
well over 10 times,

01:12:45.562 --> 01:12:46.928
and that's a big number.

01:12:46.930 --> 01:12:49.063
Now the good news
is, we can change

01:12:49.065 --> 01:12:51.966
what we eat, any
individual over night.

01:12:53.535 --> 01:12:54.936
People say, "wow, what
would happen if everybody

01:12:54.938 --> 01:12:56.637
"changed at once?"

01:12:56.639 --> 01:12:57.939
Well, that's not
going to happen.

01:12:57.941 --> 01:12:59.841
The bad news is, those
first three items,

01:12:59.843 --> 01:13:03.511
overpopulation,
over consumption,

01:13:03.513 --> 01:13:07.482
and dependence on fossil
fuels, each one of those would

01:13:07.484 --> 01:13:11.519
take decades, if not
centuries to fix.

01:13:13.489 --> 01:13:15.022
- With more
and more people embracing

01:13:15.024 --> 01:13:18.593
the idea of reducing their
intake of animal products,

01:13:18.595 --> 01:13:21.429
or adopting some kind
of a plant-based diet,

01:13:21.431 --> 01:13:24.031
it seems that things are
moving in the right direction.

01:13:24.933 --> 01:13:26.100
But are they, really?

01:13:27.603 --> 01:13:28.536
- You know, I hear people
saying, "things are

01:13:28.538 --> 01:13:29.837
"are getting better.

01:13:29.839 --> 01:13:31.806
"You know, we see
people putting solar

01:13:31.808 --> 01:13:33.508
"panels up, and more
people are eating

01:13:33.510 --> 01:13:35.676
"plant-based, and
there's vegan restaurants

01:13:35.678 --> 01:13:38.913
"going in down the street,
things are getting better."

01:13:38.915 --> 01:13:40.715
Well, not really.

01:13:40.717 --> 01:13:42.583
And not even close.

01:13:42.585 --> 01:13:43.951
For every individual,

01:13:43.953 --> 01:13:45.620
that's moving in the direction

01:13:45.622 --> 01:13:47.789
of a plant-based diet,

01:13:47.791 --> 01:13:49.791
there's a hundred people moving

01:13:49.793 --> 01:13:51.426
in the other direction.

01:13:51.428 --> 01:13:53.728
We've got to double
our food production

01:13:53.730 --> 01:13:56.597
in the next 40 years,
to feed the nine billion

01:13:56.599 --> 01:13:58.533
that we'll have by 2050.

01:14:00.636 --> 01:14:02.537
- When it
comes to global warming,

01:14:02.539 --> 01:14:04.672
the production of
animals for food

01:14:04.674 --> 01:14:07.975
currently contributes to
about 14.5% of the total

01:14:07.977 --> 01:14:10.111
global warming effect.

01:14:10.113 --> 01:14:12.079
A contribution larger
than the entire

01:14:12.081 --> 01:14:14.582
global transportation
sector combined.

01:14:15.918 --> 01:14:19.587
Livestock amounts to 53%
of nitrous oxide emissions,

01:14:20.189 --> 01:14:22.790
44% of methane gas,

01:14:22.792 --> 01:14:25.693
and 5% of the total
carbon dioxide

01:14:25.695 --> 01:14:27.595
released in our atmosphere.

01:14:32.935 --> 01:14:35.636
- Raising livestock
and eating fish,

01:14:35.638 --> 01:14:38.673
and also producing dairy
is one of the largest

01:14:38.675 --> 01:14:41.709
contributing factors
to climate change.

01:14:41.711 --> 01:14:43.544
And the public
needs to know this,

01:14:43.546 --> 01:14:46.647
and policies need to
be enacted to help

01:14:46.649 --> 01:14:46.647
eliminate that.

01:14:46.649 --> 01:14:49.550
It's one of the easiest
ways that we have

01:14:49.552 --> 01:14:53.754
to not just adapt to, but
to mitigate climate change.

01:14:53.756 --> 01:14:56.257
And it can be done as
easy as just changing

01:14:56.259 --> 01:14:57.859
out what you have on your plate.

01:15:03.632 --> 01:15:06.200
- Organic
grass fed beef

01:15:06.202 --> 01:15:08.169
seems to be the new trend.

01:15:08.171 --> 01:15:10.571
And the idea sounds
really appealing.

01:15:10.573 --> 01:15:14.542
Cows that live off grass
don't take any antibiotics,

01:15:14.544 --> 01:15:16.177
and therefore supposedly
provide a healthier

01:15:16.179 --> 01:15:19.113
food source for us,
when compared to factory

01:15:19.115 --> 01:15:21.148
farmed animals.

01:15:21.150 --> 01:15:22.817
But is there a catch?

01:15:22.819 --> 01:15:25.086
- It's a very large
movement today,

01:15:25.088 --> 01:15:26.554
and I think what's
happening is that

01:15:26.556 --> 01:15:29.590
there's been a shift
because of more and more

01:15:29.592 --> 01:15:31.592
people being concerned
about the humane

01:15:31.594 --> 01:15:33.861
raising of animals, and
moving away from factory

01:15:33.863 --> 01:15:36.998
farms, they're moving
toward grass fed operations,

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:38.633
or pasture fed operations.

01:15:38.635 --> 01:15:41.769
It's a complete fabrication
by the meat and dairy

01:15:41.771 --> 01:15:44.171
industries to
continue perpetuating

01:15:44.173 --> 01:15:46.607
the slaughtering of
animals, because even though

01:15:46.609 --> 01:15:48.609
some animal might
be humane raised,

01:15:48.611 --> 01:15:50.311
they're still not humane killed,

01:15:50.313 --> 01:15:52.747
and all of the animals
that are still placed

01:15:52.749 --> 01:15:54.215
on your plate have
to be slaughtered

01:15:54.217 --> 01:15:55.883
in some manner, and
so there's still

01:15:55.885 --> 01:15:58.019
a humane issue there,
but from an environmental

01:15:58.021 --> 01:16:01.722
standpoint, in many aspects,
raising grass fed beef

01:16:01.724 --> 01:16:05.760
is less sustainable than
factory fed animals,

01:16:05.762 --> 01:16:08.963
and the reason is, because
it's so land intensive.

01:16:08.965 --> 01:16:11.899
It may require eight
pounds of feed to produce

01:16:11.901 --> 01:16:14.201
one pound of an animal
product, if it were beef,

01:16:14.203 --> 01:16:16.971
but in a grass fed situation,
sometimes, it's 10 times

01:16:16.973 --> 01:16:20.741
that much, it may be 70,
80 times from a grass fed

01:16:20.743 --> 01:16:22.777
to a grain fed beef.

01:16:22.779 --> 01:16:24.712
Additionally, from a
climate change standpoint,

01:16:24.714 --> 01:16:26.714
grass fed cattle
produce 40 to 60%

01:16:26.716 --> 01:16:29.850
more greenhouse gas
emissions, meaning methane,

01:16:29.852 --> 01:16:31.786
carbon dioxide,
land use changes,

01:16:31.788 --> 01:16:34.088
than a grain fed cow would.

01:16:35.791 --> 01:16:37.692
- Another thing
often taken for granted

01:16:37.694 --> 01:16:39.794
is the depletion of our oceans.

01:16:40.662 --> 01:16:42.797
We often think of
fish as a never ending

01:16:42.799 --> 01:16:45.900
self replenishing food source,

01:16:45.902 --> 01:16:48.736
but the truth seems
to be quite different.

01:16:49.705 --> 01:16:52.340
- Over 90% of all the
big fish in the oceans

01:16:52.342 --> 01:16:54.342
are already gone.

01:16:54.344 --> 01:16:56.978
80% of commercial fisheries
are over exploited,

01:16:56.980 --> 01:16:58.379
or depleted.

01:16:58.381 --> 01:17:01.048
The fishing fleets are
chasing the last of the fish.

01:17:01.050 --> 01:17:02.917
And have to travel
further and further away

01:17:02.919 --> 01:17:05.686
from the land and deeper
and deeper into the ocean

01:17:05.688 --> 01:17:06.887
to catch them.

01:17:06.889 --> 01:17:08.356
I've seen illegal
fishing in Antarctica,

01:17:08.358 --> 01:17:11.058
and that's as far away
from land as you can get.

01:17:13.662 --> 01:17:15.763
- When someone sits
down at a table,

01:17:15.765 --> 01:17:18.799
to eat fish or seafood
on their plate,

01:17:19.701 --> 01:17:21.836
what they're really
doing is they're eating

01:17:21.838 --> 01:17:25.740
a target fish that's becoming
depleted to the point

01:17:25.742 --> 01:17:28.376
of near extinction,
but they're also eating

01:17:28.378 --> 01:17:31.379
baggage comes with it,
and typically it requires

01:17:31.381 --> 01:17:35.750
about five to twenty
times more other seafood,

01:17:35.752 --> 01:17:39.887
as by-kill, and
by-kill is the term

01:17:39.889 --> 01:17:42.390
that relates to all
those other sea life,

01:17:42.392 --> 01:17:45.760
living in the ocean that
are killed in the process

01:17:45.762 --> 01:17:48.396
of trying to get that
target fish to your plate,

01:17:48.398 --> 01:17:51.399
whether it's with purse
seine type of fishing method,

01:17:51.401 --> 01:17:54.368
or long line or bottom
trawling, or middle trawling,

01:17:54.370 --> 01:17:57.271
our oceans are expected
to be completely

01:17:57.273 --> 01:17:59.807
devoid of all fish
that we recognize

01:17:59.809 --> 01:18:02.109
commercially today
by the year 2048.

01:18:02.111 --> 01:18:04.011
- The oceans are
dying, and nobody wants

01:18:04.013 --> 01:18:05.413
to know about it.

01:18:05.415 --> 01:18:06.814
And if the oceans die, we die.

01:18:06.816 --> 01:18:07.848
It's as simple as that.

01:18:07.850 --> 01:18:09.917
And if you start
destroying them,

01:18:09.919 --> 01:18:11.318
you're basically
killing out the crew,

01:18:11.320 --> 01:18:12.853
and the life support
systems going to collapse,

01:18:12.855 --> 01:18:14.088
and there won't be
any air to breathe,

01:18:14.090 --> 01:18:15.356
and there won't be
any food to eat,

01:18:15.358 --> 01:18:16.157
and the climate'll
be out of control,

01:18:16.159 --> 01:18:18.292
and, not a good thing.

01:18:18.294 --> 01:18:20.261
But we have to humble
ourselves and recognize

01:18:20.263 --> 01:18:23.864
that we need this diversity,
we need these creatures,

01:18:23.866 --> 01:18:26.167
we need this interdependence,
and if we don't see that,

01:18:26.169 --> 01:18:29.770
then our chances of
survival are quite slim.

01:18:29.772 --> 01:18:31.472
My big concern is not
that we're going to wipe

01:18:31.474 --> 01:18:34.008
ourselves out, out of
sheer ecological stupidity,

01:18:34.010 --> 01:18:36.444
but that we're going to
take so much with us.

01:18:39.347 --> 01:18:41.916
- So much confusion,
and so much debate.

01:18:43.018 --> 01:18:44.885
That it just boggles
my mind that we can't

01:18:44.887 --> 01:18:46.787
think like third graders,
and say, "why not

01:18:46.789 --> 01:18:48.989
"just address the
number one cause here."

01:18:50.492 --> 01:18:53.027
You know, we got ten
holes in the boat,

01:18:53.029 --> 01:18:55.496
the boat's sinking, which
hole do we fill first?

01:18:55.498 --> 01:18:56.964
Go to the big hole.

01:18:56.966 --> 01:18:59.467
Fill that big hole first.

01:18:59.469 --> 01:19:01.035
- I mean, so often we're
looking at just what

01:19:01.037 --> 01:19:02.837
we would like to eat,
because it satisfies

01:19:02.839 --> 01:19:04.772
our taste preferences.

01:19:04.774 --> 01:19:05.940
Well, we're at a point in time,

01:19:05.942 --> 01:19:08.476
in order to save
humanity essentially,

01:19:08.478 --> 01:19:11.212
save our species, which
is not an overstatement

01:19:11.214 --> 01:19:14.982
at all, we need to start
looking outside of self,

01:19:14.984 --> 01:19:17.084
and start looking at how
our choices are fully

01:19:17.086 --> 01:19:19.053
effecting those around
us, those species

01:19:19.055 --> 01:19:21.288
that we share this planet with,

01:19:21.290 --> 01:19:23.057
and especially
future generations.

01:19:27.362 --> 01:19:28.763
- A couple
years back, I saw

01:19:28.765 --> 01:19:31.265
a documentary
called, earthlings,

